Krystle S. Morey









 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Mini estate in the Heart of Loudonville!                




See All Homes of the Day





 







 Enlarge





                Bozich with his hunting dogs inside the lobby of SI Group's Niskayuna headquarters.            

                Donna Abbott Vlahos  |  Albany Business Review            








 



Frank Bozich's career has brought him deep into mines in South Africa, through jet engine factories and to automotive plants.
It's not what you might expect from the head of SI Group, a maker of specialty resins and adhesives. Bozich has worked in the chemical field -- sometimes literally in oil fields -- for nearly 20 years. He is a former executive of several international chemical companies, including the giant BASF.









 Enlarge






                            Bozich with his hunting dogs inside the lobby of SI Group's Niskayuna headquarters.                        
Donna Abbott Vlahos  |  Albany Business Review










 


As the (relatively) new president and CEO of SI Group (he signed on a year ago), Bozich is tasked with keeping the Schenectady company ahead of the competition. One recent move: acquiring three businesses from an international competitor, making SI Group one of the largest Ibuprofen suppliers in the world.
I sat down with Bozich recently to chat about entrepreneurship, swimming and his vision for the company.
What was your first job out of college? I worked in the adhesive industry for a year and a half, for National Starch and Chemical, which is now part of Henkel, the biggest adhesive company in the world. I started as a bench chemist and after a year got a job in marketing.
You left that job while still in your early 20s? I started a small adhesive company in the Chicago area that focused on printing and publishing products. This was back when they had telephone directories. We made the adhesives that were used in book, magazine and directory binding.




What happened? My partner was a colleague at National Starch. We sold the company in 1993 to a British multinational. I continued on after it was sold. I ran operations in the Americas.
Does that experience influence your work now? By starting a company at a young age, I learned quickly what I am good at, what I am not good at, and how to focus on strengths. I also learned what it meant to make money and how to survive as a small business owner.

Where did your interest in adhesives come from? Before I started with National Starch, I was intrigued by all of the uses for adhesives. They're used in everything from automobiles to books. I got to go to breweries and see how they labeled and packaged beverages, car companies, aerospace plants ... It was interesting to see how all of these products were made with adhesives.
You have a vision for what SI Group will look like in 2020. When I met the shareholders in October 2012, they explained they wanted to take SI Group from this profitable core business that had existed for quite some time to a growth trajectory. When I joined the company, I had the benefit of talking to them about developing a strategy called Vision 2020. The world really has some specific challenges that SI Group is adept at solving. For example, energy efficiency is not going to go away. It is one of the critical global mega trends. SI Group brings solutions that enable that. If we have a strength at solving something the world needs, that is where we want to focus.
What do you look for in a recruit? You need to have curiosity and want to have that global work experience. We are not a process and procedure company. We really rely on empowered individuals. Everyone who works here can really change the destiny of the company. We don't want people to just come here for the paycheck.
You start your day with a swim at the Niskayuna pool? I swim in lane 3 at 5:30 a.m. I swam competitively and played water polo when I was young, through college. I won some events, but wasn't world-class. I like to swim for exercise. I wish I could go every day.




 


You ran BASF businesses for six years. Your takeaways? BASF is the chemical company. The scale and scope that they have is something I really admire about it. BASF is consistent. They know what they are good at and they stick to that strategy. I find that companies that are constantly trying to reinvent themselves tend to lose focus.
What are some of the patents you hold? I am a co-author on a breathable disposable diaper patent; a way to package pressure-sensitive adhesives using a sausage machine; and a technology to recycle precious metals. The first patent I was a co-author on was the glue that holds the credit card to the mail.
How many patents are in your name? Excellent question. I don't know.
Frank Bozich
